courses.learning_outcomes:
Learning goal: To become a competent and ethical research scientist who are able to offer informed solutions to key problems in global studies

Specific learning outcomes:
On completion of the course, the student shall be able to:

Knowledge:
show a nuanced understanding of the key considerations and dilemmas in research design and methods;

Skills:
Identify theoretically and practically important problems in global studies;
Display mastery of a range of methods;
Understand the connections between research problem, theory, method and expected outcomes of global studies research project;

Attitude:
Understand and internalize the ethical requirements of social science methods;
Be aware of the possible cultural, class, gender, age and other biases in research

After taking this course, students are expected to be able to:

• Demonstrate an understanding over the new trend of global communication in the twenty-first century;
• Describe the development of world communication and critically analyzes the phenomenon about media;
• Relate relevant communication and media theories to the cases;
• Engage into the debate about the paradigm of global communication;
• Develop the sensitivities in global affairs and the trend of global communication.

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:

1. Describe the evolution of the globalized culture and society and identify how different factors contribute to the formulation and transformation of global culture and society;

2. Understand the basic concepts, theories and analytical approaches in understanding the diversity of different cultural and social systems across the globe;

3. Critically analyze the basic characteristics, process of cultural globalization and its interaction with national, regional and international society;

4. Describe and analyze the roles and functions of state and non-state actors in shaping global culture and society, etc.;

5. Analyze the role and functions of communication, media and technology in the context of the globalized culture and society; and

6. Critically reflect the role and impacts of global capitalism on cultural globalization;

If possible, seminar by invited guest will be arranged to provide students with insights into the debates and controversies in contemporary world economy.

By the end of the course, students should be able:

1) To learn the skills of on-site data collection for field studies;
2) To develop abilities to assess collected data with knowledge from classroom learning;
3) To explore and develop own research topic;
4) To compare and contrast the research topic across different countries or regions; and

5) To complete a proper research report.

After taking this course, students are expected to:
• have a comprehensive understanding on the role of the Internet in the formation of the contemporary global info society and what social changes it has brought;
• be able to critically analyze social phenomenon related to the Internet;
• be able to use the concepts and knowledge gained to provide innovative solutions for globally social problems brought the Internet.

By the end of the course students should be able to:
1) identify the concepts and key features of the Chinese foreign policies;
2) identify the relationship between China with other nations, notably the U.S., BRICS and its neighbours in Asia-Pacific;
3) identify the driving forces of Chinese foreign and security policies;
4) identify the changes and continuities in Chinese foreign policies;
5) assess critically the impact of different policies towards the Global Governance;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to Chinese foreign policies: a historical overview since 1949;
2) Analytical Framework in formulating foreign policies: the Party, the Bureaucrats, the think-tanks, the Military and Public Opinions;
3) Chinese national security and strategic culture: its IR view and impact on foreign policies;
4) China's conception of Sovereignty and International Order
5) Chinese foreign relations with Asia, Latin America, Africa and Middle East;
6) Chinese foreign relations with Europe and North America;
7) Relations with major powers: US, Japan and Russia;
8) China's role in Global Governance: Trade and Security;
9) China turns to Multilateralism;
10) China and the peripheries: Tibet, Xinjiang, Taiwan and Hong Kong.

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Lai Hongyi, The Domestic Sources of China's Foreign Policy: Regimes, Leadership, Priorities and Processes, (Oxon: Routledge, 2010);
2) Susan Shirk, China: Fragile Superpower, (New York: Oxford University Press, 2008);
3) Wang Gangwu & Zheng Yongnian (eds.), China and the New International Order, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008);
4) Alastair Iain Johnston, Social States: China in International Institutions, 1980-2000, (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 2008);
5) Robert G. Sutter, Chinese Foreign Relations: Power and Policy since the Cold War, 3rd edition, (Lanham: Rowman & Littlefield, 2012);
6) Guoguang Wu & Helen Lansdowne (eds.), China Turns to Multilateralism: Foreign policy and Regional Security, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008).

courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students are expected to:

• Demonstrate a comprehensive understanding over the major concepts, theories, and cases in the development of globalization and cultural psychology;
• Describe the phenomenon of the globalization, and analyze the impacts on cultural psychology;
• Relate theories and concepts to globalization and cultural psychology as a discipline;
• Engage into the debates of those impacts of the globalization and present their ideas;
• Develop presentation, analytical, and communication skills through group-based work.

By the end of the course, students are expected to:

• Demonstrate a comprehensive understanding over the major concepts, theories, and cases in the development of international relations and international law;
• Describe and analyze the evolution of the international system, and transformation of the international law in the 21st Century;
• Critically assess different theoretical approaches to international relations and apply various concepts into the practice of the international laws;
• Engage into the debates of those controversial cases in international politics and present their distinctive viewpoints with evidence-based knowledge;
• Situate international laws in the international politics context.

By the end of the course student should be able to:
1) identify the differences and relations between various cultures and their respective interpretations on several agenda-items in the Global Community;
2) identify and assess critically the integrity and validity of the interpretations;
3) relate contents with their daily life examples;
4) think critically

After taking this course, students are expected to be able to:

• Identify the role, functions and major dynamics of multinational corporations in the global economy;
• Critically assess the influence of the multinational corporations in the global age;
• Apply relevant theories to analyze different multinational corporation cases;
• Connect the global business development with various types of political, economic and legal systems in different countries;
• Engage multinational corporations into the debate of international political economy.

After taking this course, students are expected to:
• describe and discuss the goals, structures, functions and operations of an organization in the non-government or public sector;
• identify the professional skills required in managing such an organization;
• apply some of the concepts and skills learnt in the programme in a real work setting;
• put into practice attitudes and personal values in accordance with the requirements of working in the sector;
• identify own strengths and weaknesses with regard to employment in the sector.
• prepare for an relevant global exposure in the student exchange program

By the end of the course students should be able to :
1) identify the mainstream theories regarding Strategic studies and security studies and assess their usefulness in explaining the phenomenon and behaviours;
2) identify the differences/similarities between the different schools of thoughts in relation to strategic studies;
3) identify the major traditional security challenges confronted by nation-states and global governance nowadays;
4) assess the importance of traditional security challenges to us;
5) relate the content with different policies undertaken by different countries;
6) think critically

courses.course_syllabus:
1) Introduction to strategic studies and security studies;
2) Overview of Military Technology and Strategic thinking of the Major Powers: Air, Land and Sea Power ;
3) Strategic Studies from the East: Sun Tsz and others;
4) Strategic Studies from the West: Clausewitz and others;
5) IR Theories and Strategic Studies;
6) Theories and Practices of Conflict Resolution;
7) History of War;
8) Perception and the Threat of Force: Nuclear Deterrence and WMD;
9) Alliance System;
10) Individuals, Regional Security Institutions, the United Nations Security Council in peacekeeping;
11) Democracy and Peace;
12) Assessment of the level of threats imposed by "Traditional" Security Threats under Globalization: Opportunities and Challenges

courses.required_readings:
1) Thomas G. Mahnken & Joseph A. Maiolo (eds.), Strategic Studies: A Reader, (Oxon: Routledge, 2008);
2) John Baylis, James J. Wirtz & Colin S. Gray (eds.), Strategy in the Contemporary World, 3rd edition, (London: Oxford University Press, 2010);
3) Paul D. Williams (ed.), Security Studies: An Introduction, 2nd edition, (Oxon: Routledge, 2012).

courses.recommended_readings:
1) Colin S. Gray, Modern Strategy, (Oxon: Oxford University Press, 1999);
2) David Jordan & James D. Kiras (eds.), Understanding Modern Warfare, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2008);
3) Michael E. Brown, et al(eds.), Theories of War and Peace, (Cambridge: MIT Press; 1998);
4) Bradley S. Klein, Strategic Studies and World Order; The Global Politics of Deterrence, (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1994);
5) Carl von Clausewitz, On War, (Oxford: Oxford University Press), 2007;
6) Sun Tzu, The Art of War, (New York: Cosmio, 2006);
7) Peter Wallensteen, Understanding Conflict Resolution: War, Peace and the Global System, 3rd edition, (London: SAGE Publications, 2011);
8) Hew Strachan & Andreas Herberg-Rothe (eds.), Clausewitz in the Twenty-first Century, (Oxon: Oxford University Press, 2007).
